  "text": "Hydralazine is associated with both drug-induced lupus and vasculitis. Hydralazine-induced lupus is JAAD CASE REPORTS VOLUME 5, NUMBER 11 both a more commonly reported (incidence of approximately 5%-10% per year of therapy) and more benign entity compared with hydralazineinduced vasculitis, which can present with severe pulmonary and renal involvement. [CITATION_1] As our patient exemplifies, considerable overlap exists between these 2 conditions. [CITATION_2] A history of joint pain and normocytic anemia, as well as positive ANA, antidsDNA, and anti-histone antibodies, are consistent with drug-induced lupus, whereas dermal vessel necrosis with positive p-ANCA and anti-MPO antibodies point toward drug-induced vasculitis. It is thought that hydralazine induces autoimmunity by accumulating in neutrophils and causing apoptosis, thus exposing normally sequestered cell antigens to the immune system and leading to the formation of various autoantibodies (ANA, anti-dsDNA, antihistone, ANCA) [CITATION_3] ; this may explain the overlapping serologies seen in our patient.",
